<taxonomicName id="4C714FB4FFA4FF8FF681F98659DAF9E1" authority="Zhang &amp; Viraktamath, 2010" authorityName="Zhang &amp; Viraktamath" authorityYear="2010" box="[745,1182,1605,1630]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pedionis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lii" subGenus="Pedionis">
<emphasis id="B905E825FFA4FF8FF681F9865FB3F9E2" box="[745,759,1606,1629]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="113">P</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis id="B905E825FFA4FF8FF779F9865E5BF9E2" box="[785,799,1606,1629]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="113">P</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis id="B905E825FFA4FF8FF751F9855E14F9E1" box="[825,848,1605,1630]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="113">lii</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFE049C6FFA4FF8FF732F98559DAF9E1" author="Zhang" box="[858,1182,1605,1630]" pageId="1" pageNumber="113" refString="Zhang, B. &amp; Viraktamath, C. A. (2010) New species of macropsine leafhopper genus Pedionis Hamilton (Hemiptera, Cicadellidae) from China, with a key to Chinese species. Zootaxa, 2484, 53 - 60." type="journal article" year="2010">Zhang &amp; Viraktamath, 2010</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C714FB4FFA4FF8FF0B2F9865C2CF93D" authority="Viraktamath, 1981" authorityName="Viraktamath" authorityYear="1981" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pedionis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palniensis" subGenus="Pedionis">
<emphasis id="B905E825FFA4FF8FF0B2F98659ACF9E2" box="[1242,1256,1606,1629]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="113">P</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis id="B905E825FFA4FF8FF16AF9865854F9E2" box="[1282,1296,1606,1629]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="113">P</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis id="B905E825FFA4FF8FF142F98558D8F9E1" box="[1322,1436,1605,1630]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="113">palniensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFE049C6FFA4FF8FF4FFF9A95C2CF93D" author="Viraktamath" box="[151,360,1641,1666]" pageId="1" pageNumber="113" refString="Viraktamath, C. A. (1981) Indian Macropsinae (Homoptera: Cicadellidae). II. Species described by W. L. Distant and descriptions of new species from the Indian subcontinent. Entomologica Scandinavica, 12, 295 - 310. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631281794709791" type="journal article" year="1981">
Viraktamath, 
<quantity id="4C8999D2FFA4FF8FF558F9AA5C2CF93D" box="[304,360,1642,1666]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.03174" pageId="1" pageNumber="113" unit="in" value="1981.0">1981</quantity>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in body coloration but can be distinguished by the aedeagus without lateral processes and with shaft not tumid at middle; dorsal connective with long and slender process; and pygofer ventral margin with small spines and setae apically, and acute apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36B67BCFFA4FF8CF4AFF9155981FD71" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="114" pageId="1" pageNumber="113" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BCE3437FFA4FF8FF4AFF9155819F8C1" blockId="1.[151,1437,1497,2026]" pageId="1" pageNumber="113">
<emphasis id="B905E825FFA4FF8FF4AFF9155C1DF951" bold="true" box="[199,345,1749,1774]" pageId="1" pageNumber="113">Description.</emphasis>
Body background coloration (Fig. 1A–C) evenly dark brown, striations and punctations on surface of crown, face, pronotum and scutellum darker. Face yellowish, with pair of longitudinal cibarial muscle impressions in central part on both sides of midline contrasting sharply against surrounding areas due to different sculpture of cuticle and almost complete absence of brown dots, eyes pale brown, ocelli milky white, anteclypeus black. Pronotum and scutellum brown. Forewing venation black with white spots. Legs with black markings.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCE3437FFA4FF8CF4AFF8495E34FF47" blockId="1.[151,1437,1497,2026]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,151,792]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="114" pageId="1" pageNumber="113">Body form (Fig. 1A–C) stout, wedge shaped. Crown very short in dorsal view, arched apically, head including eyes narrower than pronotum. Face across eyes slightly wider than long, densely punctured, frons with medial longitudinal carina, distance between ocelli nearly 5.5 × as long as that from ocellus to adjacent eye, anteclypeus projected beyond gena. Pronotum strongly declivous onward and bilaterally, with longitudinal carina in middle, about 2.6 × wider than long. Scutellum with rough surface, 1.6 × longer than pronotum, suture between mesonotum and scutellum well developed. Forewing broad, veins prominent.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCE3437FFA7FF8CF4AFFEC45951FD82" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,792]" pageId="2" pageNumber="114">
<emphasis id="B905E825FFA7FF8CF4AFFEC45C2BFEA2" box="[199,367,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="114">Male genitalia</emphasis>
. Pygofer (
<figureCitation id="134A28B2FFA7FF8CF584FEC45F76FEA3" box="[492,562,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1526,1548]" captionTargetBox="[160,1414,214,1470]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1505]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pedionis (Pedionis) damingshanensis sp. nov. A. Pygofer side, lateral view; B. Pygofer ventral process, ventral view; C. Subgenital plate, lateral view; D. Aedeagus, lateral view; E. Aedeagus, ventral view; F. Dorsal connective, lateral view; G. Style, dorsal view; H. Connective, dorsal view; I. Connective, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/831668/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="114">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
A) nearly triangular, broad basally, dorsal margin declivous caudoventrally, tapered to pointed end, apical half of ventral margin (
<figureCitation id="134A28B2FFA7FF8CF69AFEE75E72FEFF" box="[754,822,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1526,1548]" captionTargetBox="[160,1414,214,1470]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1505]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pedionis (Pedionis) damingshanensis sp. nov. A. Pygofer side, lateral view; B. Pygofer ventral process, ventral view; C. Subgenital plate, lateral view; D. Aedeagus, lateral view; E. Aedeagus, ventral view; F. Dorsal connective, lateral view; G. Style, dorsal view; H. Connective, dorsal view; I. Connective, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/831668/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="114">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
B) with some small spines and setae, apex extended to acute tip. Subgenital plate (
<figureCitation id="134A28B2FFA7FF8CF5A1FE8C5F48FEDB" box="[457,524,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1526,1548]" captionTargetBox="[160,1414,214,1470]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1505]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pedionis (Pedionis) damingshanensis sp. nov. A. Pygofer side, lateral view; B. Pygofer ventral process, ventral view; C. Subgenital plate, lateral view; D. Aedeagus, lateral view; E. Aedeagus, ventral view; F. Dorsal connective, lateral view; G. Style, dorsal view; H. Connective, dorsal view; I. Connective, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/831668/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="114">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
C) slender, almost parallel margined, shorter than ventral margin of pygofer, with round apex; fine setae densely distributed on lower margin, sparsely on upper margin, and cluster of long setae distally. Aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="134A28B2FFA7FF8CF51CFE545CF3FE13" box="[372,439,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1526,1548]" captionTargetBox="[160,1414,214,1470]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1505]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pedionis (Pedionis) damingshanensis sp. nov. A. Pygofer side, lateral view; B. Pygofer ventral process, ventral view; C. Subgenital plate, lateral view; D. Aedeagus, lateral view; E. Aedeagus, ventral view; F. Dorsal connective, lateral view; G. Style, dorsal view; H. Connective, dorsal view; I. Connective, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/831668/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="114">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
D–E) broad basally, with distal half strongly sinuate in lateral view, apex twisted dorsad; in ventral view, shaft gradually tapered to truncate end, gonopore apical. Dorsal connective (
<figureCitation id="134A28B2FFA7FF8CF0D4FE775844FE6F" box="[1212,1280,439,464]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1526,1548]" captionTargetBox="[160,1414,214,1470]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1505]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pedionis (Pedionis) damingshanensis sp. nov. A. Pygofer side, lateral view; B. Pygofer ventral process, ventral view; C. Subgenital plate, lateral view; D. Aedeagus, lateral view; E. Aedeagus, ventral view; F. Dorsal connective, lateral view; G. Style, dorsal view; H. Connective, dorsal view; I. Connective, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/831668/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="114">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
F) developed, broad and compressed, apical process slender, long, and tapered to pointed apex, slightly and evenly arcuate through most of length. Style (
<figureCitation id="134A28B2FFA7FF8CF586FE3F5F75FDA7" box="[494,561,511,536]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1526,1548]" captionTargetBox="[160,1414,214,1470]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1505]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pedionis (Pedionis) damingshanensis sp. nov. A. Pygofer side, lateral view; B. Pygofer ventral process, ventral view; C. Subgenital plate, lateral view; D. Aedeagus, lateral view; E. Aedeagus, ventral view; F. Dorsal connective, lateral view; G. Style, dorsal view; H. Connective, dorsal view; I. Connective, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/831668/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="114">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
G) slender, angled on basal 2/5, stem slightly sinuate, apex abruptly narrowed and reflexed, with bluntly rounded tip. Connective (
<figureCitation id="134A28B2FFA7FF8CF6B4FDE45E5BFD83" box="[732,799,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1526,1548]" captionTargetBox="[160,1414,214,1470]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1505]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pedionis (Pedionis) damingshanensis sp. nov. A. Pygofer side, lateral view; B. Pygofer ventral process, ventral view; C. Subgenital plate, lateral view; D. Aedeagus, lateral view; E. Aedeagus, ventral view; F. Dorsal connective, lateral view; G. Style, dorsal view; H. Connective, dorsal view; I. Connective, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/831668/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="114">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
H–I) typical of genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCE3437FFA7FF8CF4AFFD8A5F7DFD14" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,792]" pageId="2" pageNumber="114">
<emphasis id="B905E825FFA7FF8CF4AFFD8A5C5FFDDC" box="[199,283,586,611]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="114">Female</emphasis>
. Body coloration pattern and appearance similar to male, but form slightly more robust. 7th sternite broad, hind margin sinuated, excavated medially, length of midline about 2.0 × as long as sixth sternite. Ovipositor definitely projecting beyond pygofer.
</paragraph>
